Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-18

Title   : Trump ally Stephen Miran casts lone dissent at the Fed 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-18T04:19:59
Fetched : 2025-09-18T06:41:46.102250
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/trump-ally-stephen-miran-casts-lone-dissent-at-the-fed/slideshow/123963557.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
President Trump placed close ally Stephen Miran at the Federal Reserve with hopes he could push for deeper rate cuts. But while the Fed delivered a quarter-point reduction, Miran stood alone in calling for a more aggressive half-point move. (Source: Reuters)
ETMarkets.com
2/7
Miran’s Dissent
Sworn in just before the meeting, Miran quickly made his mark by casting the only vote for a 50-basis-point cut. All other policymakers — including Trump appointees Christopher Waller and Michelle Bowman — backed the smaller 25-basis-point reduction.
NYT News Service
3/7
Market Impact
Despite being outvoted, Miran’s dissent grabbed headlines. His rate-path projection, which implied another 125 basis points of cuts by year-end, was the most aggressive forecast among Fed officials, catching the attention of analysts and investors.
TIL Creatives
4/7
Powell’s Response
Fed Chair Jerome Powell stressed there was no broad support for a 50-basis-point cut. He noted that while differing views are normal, the committee acted with “a high degree of unity,” underscoring the Fed’s independence from political pressure.
AP
5/7
Trump Appointees’ Stance
Although Waller and Bowman had dissented in July, they did not align with Miran this time, instead supporting the majority decision. Analysts saw this as a signal of confidence in the Fed’s institutional independence.
IANS
6/7
Analysts Weigh In
Miran’s outlook drew scrutiny. TD Securities noted his projection of 2.875% for 2025 echoed Trump’s push for rapid rate normalization. Others dismissed it as unrealistic, with one economist remarking that “Miran’s dots stand out like a sore thumb.”
Reuters
7/7
What’s Next?
Under Fed rules, Miran cannot speak publicly until Friday. Markets will then get more detail on his reasoning. At his confirmation hearing, he argued tariffs were not fueling inflation and suggested tighter immigration policies could ease housing demand by reducing rental pressures.
(Disclaimer: This slideshow has been sourced from Reuters)

