Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-18

Title   : Urban Company makes strong listing debut 
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-17T15:30:11
Fetched : 2025-09-18T06:50:06.143535
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/markets/urban-company-makes-strong-listing-debut/article70062433.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Home and beauty services provider Urban Company made a strong debut on the bourses, listing at over 57 per cent premium and ending 64 per cent higher from its issue price.
It zoomed 74 per cent intra-day to a high of ₹179 before settling down at ₹169 on the BSE, with a market value close to $3 billion. It listed at ₹162.25, against the issue price of ₹103 a share.
This is the third IPO in Dutch investment group Prosus’ India portfolio, after Swiggy and Bluestone.
It has around 7 per cent stake in the company, having recently raised stake just prior to the IPO.
“At the core, I do believe this is an extremely special company,” Ashutosh Sharma, who leads the India and South-East Asia investments of Prosus.
Staying the course
He pointed out that while many home and beauty services company had started more than a decade ago, it was only Urban Company that had stayed the course. “The reason is this: The services are non-standard,” he said, explaining that it differed for each customer.
“It’s an extremely hard sector and they have really flagged it amazingly well,” he told businessline in a chat. “They are barely scratching the surface compared to the population of our country.”
Prosus first invested in Urban Company in 2021 and has been steadily increasing stake since then. Sharma said that he was not averse to buying more stake if the opportunity arose.
Urban Company was set up in 2014 by Abhiraj Singh Bhal, Varun Khaitan and Raghav Chandra with the aim to provide a range of services at home including plumbing, home repairs, cleaning, maintenance of appliances, as well as beauty services.
The company’s revenue rose 38 per cent on year in FY25, while it has also turned profitable.
Structural long-term play
Market experts are seeing the listing as a structural long-term play on digital adoption and formalisation of the unorganised sector.
“This IPO is a milestone in our journey, but it is only the beginning of the next phase of growth,” said Bhal.
“As we step into the public market, we remain committed to long-term value creation for our customers, partners and investors,” he added.
Published on September 17, 2025

