Title   : SEBI’s equity reclassification to be a game-changer for REITs: Embassy REIT CEO 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-18T03:30:00
Fetched : 2025-09-18T07:21:37.009503
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/digital-real-estate/realty-news/sebis-equity-reclassification-to-be-a-game-changer-for-reits-embassy-reit-ceo/articleshow/123938797.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Amit Shetty, CEO of Embassy REIT, believes the move will be a game-changer, unlocking the next phase of growth for India’s REIT market.
According to him, the reclassification will not only enhance liquidity and pave the way for potential index inclusion but also attract broader investor participation, especially through mutual funds, positioning REITs as a mainstream investment avenue for long-term wealth creation. Edited Excerpts –
Q) What is your take on SEBI approving the re-classification of REITs as equity?
A) We welcome and commend SEBI’s landmark move to re-classify REITs as equity. As pioneers of REITs in India and long-time champions of the asset class, we at Embassy REIT see this move as a catalyst for the next phase of growth.
This move paves the way for broader investor participation, stronger liquidity, and potential index inclusion, all of which help position REITs as a mainstream investment option.
For investors, this change signals greater clarity and confidence in REITs as a long-term wealth-creation vehicle.
Q) How will this reclassification affect mutual fund investments in REITs?
A) By treating REITs as equity, mutual funds can now invest more freely in them without being constrained by the earlier hybrid classification.
This will allow equity mutual funds to meaningfully increase allocations to REITs, providing retail investors indirect access through their fund holdings.
The outcome will be broader participation and deeper penetration of REITs into India’s household savings.
Currently, mutual fund participation in REITs is less than 0.5%, but this reclassification can take that significantly higher.
Further, with potential index inclusion, REITs could see substantial passive inflows, given that index mutual funds together manage around ₹12 lakh crores of assets under management and today have virtually no exposure to the REIT space.
Q) What might be the advantages and risks for investors (especially mutual funds) due to REITs now being classified as equity?
A) REITs are high-dividend yielding, low-beta instruments that have collectively distributed nearly ₹24,000 crores over the last six years. Their classification as equity makes the product even more compelling.
Investors now gain exposure to high-quality, income-generating commercial real estate through a listed, transparent vehicle, firmly placed in the equity bucket.
For mutual funds, this improves diversification, offering steady yields and capital appreciation potential alongside traditional stocks.
While REITs will be influenced by broader equity market movements, they are inherently less volatile than many equities.
The contracted cash flows of Grade-A office assets, backed by long leases and marquee occupiers, provide a stability and predictability not seen in many other equity products.
Q) How could this change influence liquidity in the REIT market in India?
A) Liquidity is likely to see a meaningful uplift. With equity funds and indices opening up to REITs, we expect higher trading volumes, better price discovery and higher inflows.
For the broader market, this creates a virtuous cycle - more liquidity draws more investors, which in turn enhances the attractiveness of REITs as a listed asset class.
Q) Do you think treating REITs as equity aligns with global best practices? What are examples from other countries?
A) Absolutely. Globally, REITs are classified and treated as equity. In the US, which has the most developed REIT market, REITs are a staple part of equity indices like the S&P 500.
Similarly, in markets like Singapore, Australia, and Japan, REITs are well-established as equity instruments, attracting both institutional and retail capital. India aligning with this practice will help integrate our REITs into global fund flows.
Q) Could this spur more REIT listings in India, or more capital flowing into real estate via REITs?
A) Yes, this move is truly catalytic. India’s office stock stands at nearly 800 msf, of which about 550 msf is Grade-A institutional quality. Yet only 130 msf of operational stock is currently within listed REITs, highlighting the immense headroom for growth.
In comparison, in the US, nearly 90% of institutional-grade stock sits with REITs, underscoring the potential ahead for this asset class in India.
With stronger investor appetite and index inclusion prospects, sponsors will have greater incentive to list new REITs. We could see more high-quality office and retail portfolios come to market, providing investors with a wider set of choices.
Importantly, it will channel more long-term capital into India’s real estate sector, supporting the next wave of urban growth and infrastructure creation.
(Disclaimer: Recommendations, suggestions, views, and opinions given by experts are their own. These do not represent the views of the Economic Times)
