Title   : Dixon Technologies shares in focus on Rs 553 crore acquisition for 51% stake in Q Tech Microelectronics 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-18T03:57:22
Fetched : 2025-09-18T07:56:36.220520
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/dixon-technologies-shares-in-focus-on-rs-553-crore-acquisition-for-51-stake-in-q-tech-microelectronics/articleshow/123962954.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In a filing with the stock exchanges, Dixon said it has entered into a Share Subscription and Purchase Agreement (SSPA) with Q Technology (Singapore) Pte Ltd and Kunshan Q Technology International to acquire the controlling stake. The target company manufactures camera and fingerprint modules for mobile phones, IoT devices, and the automotive sector.
The deal will be executed in two stages. First, Dixon will acquire 1.61 crore equity shares from existing shareholders — Q Tech Singapore and Q Tech International — for Rs 427.99 crore.
In the second stage, it will subscribe to 47.17 lakh fresh shares for Rs 124.99 crore. The total cash investment amounts to Rs 552.99 crore.
Upon completion of the transaction, Dixon will hold 2.08 crore shares, representing 51% of the target company’s fully diluted equity share capital.
The target company, incorporated in 2019 and headquartered in Janakpuri, New Delhi, operates in a niche but expanding segment. It manufactures and supplies camera modules and fingerprint sensors used in mobile handsets and connected devices, while also catering to the automotive sector, where demand for electronic components is steadily rising.
For FY25, the company reported a turnover of Rs 1,977 crore, compared with Rs 2,435 crore in FY24 and Rs 1,899 crore in FY23. However, its net worth remained negative at Rs 274.24 crore as of March 31, 2025.
Dixon said the acquisition will enhance its capabilities in mobile, IoT, and automotive electronics, while strengthening backward integration to gain greater supply chain control. The company noted that the deal aligns with its long-term vision of becoming a leading player in India’s electronics manufacturing space, unlocking synergies, enabling faster go-to-market strategies, and improving execution in high-demand verticals.
The transaction is subject to regulatory approvals and other closing conditions, with completion expected within 90 days of signing. The acquisition will be entirely funded through cash, with no share swap or alternative mechanism involved.
On Wednesday, Dixon Technologies’ shares closed flat at Rs 18,100.80 on BSE.
