Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-18

Title   : Infosys, LTIMindtree shares rally up to 3% on hopes of 2 more rate cuts by US Fed in 2025 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-18T05:33:43
Fetched : 2025-09-18T08:14:00.158052
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/infosys-ltimindtree-shares-rally-up-to-3-on-hopes-of-2-more-rate-cuts-by-us-fed-in-2025/articleshow/123965145.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LTIMindtree led the pack with gains of over 3% to its day high of Rs 5,609 on the NSE, followed by Infosys rising 2% to Rs 1,555 per share. Wipro, TCS, HCL Tech, and Tech Mahindra also edged higher by over a per cent in the morning. As a result, the IT index was the top-performing index, rising over 1%.
“In India, the Fed's actions could attract foreign capital, strengthening the rupee and benefiting sectors like information technology,” Rajesh Palviya, Senior Vice President of Research at Axis Securities, said.
“When combined with domestic factors, including the RBI's earlier interest rate reductions, specifically a 50 basis point cut in June 2025 and another cut in April, as well as GST rate rationalisation and various measures to boost consumption, the outlook for India's economy appears strong,” he added.
The development gains significance for the sector as companies derive a significant portion of their revenue from the US. Lower US rates reduce borrowing costs, support consumer spending, and make it easier for corporates to maintain or increase tech budgets, thereby improving the revenue visibility for Indian IT firms.
Also read: Cochin Shipyard shares jump 3% after securing Rs 200 crore work order from ONGC
Last night, the US Federal Reserve cut interest rates for the first time this year, lowering its benchmark policy rate by 25 basis points to the 4%-4.25% range. The move marks the beginning of a monetary easing cycle aimed at supporting a slowing labour market, even as inflation remains elevated.
Markets, however, expect a series of cuts through 2025 and into 2026, with some forecasts pointing to as many as six more 25 bps reductions by the end of next year. Much, however, hinges on the path of inflation and the resilience of the broader economy.
Apurva Sheth, Head of Market Perspectives and Research at SAMCO Securities, said the Fed is attempting to strike a difficult balance. “The Fed chief voiced concerns about softening in the labour market, which prompted them to cut rates. However, he also voiced concerns about the impact tariffs are having on the prices of goods, which will eventually affect consumers’ wallets.
We believe that the Fed is walking a tight rope of balancing growth and inflation. So far, the corporations have been slow in passing the tariff hikes to consumers. If they delay too much, then that will affect their profitability. If they pass on the costs, then it will lead to inflation. Neither these scenarios is good for the markets. But why bother now when you can worry about it later,” he said.
The next Fed Meeting is scheduled for October 28-29, and the last for the year will commence on December 9.
At about 9:45 am, the Nifty IT index was quoting at 36,938, higher by 1.44% from the last close. The index is down nearly 15% on a year-to-date basis.
